post_text:
While CCSD93 is still working on plans for the start of the 2020-21 school year, one thing is for sure: Jay Stream’s all new STEM Wing will be ready to help students achieve greater heights in the fields of science, technology, engineering and math whenever they do return to school!

The four classrooms along the school's east side have been renovated, and a 5,000 square foot addition has been built off of that, which will result in:
- Six STEM labs
- A domed virtual reality room
- A dedicated research and design space
- A collaboration area for staff

Built for flexibility with embedded technology and modern and future STEM concepts in mind, the space will fit the needs of any learning opportunities our students will be challenged to take on. Students will be able to seamlessly work on independent or collaborative projects that require them to design and build, interact with robotics, apply computer coding skills, and more.

Construction is ahead of schedule. Here’s a look at the progress so far!

post_text: Last week, Cloverdale and Roy DeShane 5th graders were able to celebrate graduation from their virtual D.A.R.E. program with a special visit from Carol Stream Police Officer Pablo Castro, who also serves as Jay Stream Middle School's resource officer and CCSD93's D.A.R.E. officer. post_text:
Happy #EarthDay! Before school closures, Cloverdale School 5th graders spent time this year beautifying school grounds and nearby areas along Merbach Drive as the classes took turns participating in the Village of Carol Stream's Adopt-a-Highway program, ensuring the road remained clean and clear of debris.

The activity tied in with the grade level's broader lessons on volunteerism, positive citizenship, and taking care of the community. It also reinforced crucial 21st century skills and abilities, like environmental literacy and global awareness, as well as a commitment to best practices in sustainability. Way to go Coyotes!

Before school closures, Cloverdale School 5th graders spent time this year beautifying school grounds and nearby areas along Merbach Drive as the classes took turns participating in the Village of Carol Stream's Adopt-a-Highway program, ensuring the road remained clean and clear of debris.

It also reinforced crucial 21st century skills and abilities, like environmental literacy and global awareness, as well as a commitment to best practices in sustainability. Way to go Coyotes!

post_text:
Happy Earth Day! All CCSD93 schools are committed to sustainability, with advanced recycling and composting programs, student ecology and earth clubs, and consistent environmental education when school is in session.

Special shout out to Elsie Johnson School, which was awarded the Hanover Park Village Environmental Award this year for their exceptional commitment to sustainability! In the past year, Elsie Johnson School has kept Nautilus Lane clean through the Adopt-a-Street program and earned a Water Quality Flag from the DuPage County Stormwater Committee by participating in activities to understand and improve water quality. The school made such an impression on Hanover Park that they resurrected the Environmental Award after not giving it out for several years.

post_text: As part of our ongoing 100th anniversary celebration, @CCSD93 is highlighting our history with special Talk D93 podcast episodes. Before school closures, Superintendent Hill sat down with CCSD93’s second full-time Superintendent of Schools John DiBuono to discuss his tenure from 1982 to 1996, during which CCSD93 became the fastest-growing school district in the state. Listen to learn more about this fascinating time of great expansion and much construction from the man who led the district through it!

post_text: Before spring break, students in Mrs. Munter and Mrs. Cassidy’s 4th grade class at Elsie Johnson wrote personal letters of thanks and encouragement to healthcare workers in COVID-19 ICU and ER units across the country for their extraordinary efforts at this time. The letters were mailed out. View the heartfelt response that Pat, an ER/trauma nurse in San Francisco who sees dozens of potential COVID-19 patients each shift, had when he received some of the class letters, along with copies of a few of the letters here!

post_text:
Today, staff members across CCSD93 honored and celebrated the life of Sue Rothlisberger, a CCSD93 staff member of nearly 20 years who tragically and unexpectedly passed on February 21, by wearing green, her favorite color.

Mrs. Rothlisberger most recently served as a paraprofessional in a Specialized Academic Classroom at Elsie Johnson School and always worked passionately to help her students adopt new skills and make connections with one another and with their learning. She was an outstanding and dedicated educator, and we were lucky to have her as a member of the CCSD93 family. We are sending our thoughts, prayers, and love to Mrs. Rothlisberger and her family.

post_text:
Listen to the latest episode of Talk D93, CCSD93's offical podcast!

As CCSD93 celebrates its 100th anniversary as a school district, Dr. Hill sits down with Carol Stream historian and former CCSD93 staff member Carole Ellermeier to talk about the history of CCSD93 from prior to its organization in 1920 through the tenure of its first full-time Superintendent of Schools, Dr. Elsie Johnson ending in 1982. Listen to learn how CCSD93 developed from a rural farmhouse with 18 students to a thriving suburban school district.

post_text: This week, CCSD93 Orchestra Director Marlyn Berrera was presented with the Emerging Educator Award from the Illinois American String Teachers Association during the 4th and 6th grade Orchestra concert at Stratford! The award is given to one Illinois teacher currently in their 3rd-5th year of teaching in a school orchestra setting who has achieved and maintained excellence in their program through the use of innovative teaching techniques and creative connections with the community! Congratulations Ms. Berrera!

The award is given to one Illinois teacher currently in their 3rd-5th year of teaching in a school orchestra setting who has achieved and maintained excellence in their program through the use of innovative teaching techniques and creative connections with the community! Congratulations Ms. Berrera!

post_text: Jay Stream students in Mrs. Nauert's 6th grade advanced humanities class recently paired up to research global catastrophes that cannot entirely be classified as "natural disasters," uncovering their unnatural causes in the process. Each group then studied the impact of their disaster on the environment, politics, society, and economy of the region where it occurred and the world. Finally, the partners developed an action plan to prevent or limit the effects of similar catastrophes in the future. Today the students presented their findings in the Jay Stream Innovation Center Presentation Lounge. Find out more about this engaging, relevant project!

post_text:
On Saturday, Jay Stream and Stratford, along with Keller and Addams middle schools from School District 54, played to a packed house in CCSD93’s first ever Unified Sports Basketball Tournament! Each team in this inclusive event was comprised of students with disabilities and students without.

Students and fans alike enjoyed an electric atmosphere, thrilling competition, and excellent sportsmanship. Special thanks to the referees, who made a concerted effort to continue to teach the game and ensure all participants had opportunities to show off the skills that they’ve learned throughout their Unified Sports experience!

The event truly provided equitable opportunities for those who may not otherwise have the chance to participate in extracurricular sports.

post_text:
Students in the 4th and 5th grade Magnet program at Roy DeShane have learned about the human body through an immersive unit where they’ve passed “medical exams,” becoming specialists, like neurologists and cardiologists, in different body systems. They also served as publicists, creating advertisements for their “hospital.”

Yesterday, their unit concluded as they treated visiting “patients” by researching their symptoms, coming up with diagnoses, and prescribing medications! What an engaging and relevant educational experience!

post_text:
Congratulations to Elsie Johnson School students and families for raising $1,094.04 for the American Heart Association (AHA) for lifesaving research!

The fundraising campaign began last month with an AHA kickoff assembly where Expect Respect Club students taught their peers key methods to reduce stress and maintain health like eating well, avoiding tobacco, engaging in physical activity, being prepared, and showing kindness to one another through characters called Heart Heroes. Expect Respect students further partnered with the AHA to provide classmates with daily heart-healthy tips during the morning announcements. Way to go Jaguars!

post_text: Today, students in Ms. Kolling's 6th grade class at Jay Stream Middle School put on their rendition of "The Sound of Music: The Story of Orpheus & Eurydice" after studying ancient civilizations. Students created the sets, engineered the lighting, developed promotional materials, and acted the play for peers, parents, and teachers. While this kind of performance is an annual tradition for Ms. Kolling's class, this year was the first time the students were able to use the newly redesigned Innovation Center's stage area for the performance!

post_text:
Join the Birth To 5 Community Coalition for Let’s Play! free indoor play and resource fair on 2/1 from 10am-1pm at Stratford Middle School!

It's designed for families with children ages birth through 5 and will feature multiple indoor play stations with activities especially for young children as well as helpful resources from a variety of local organizations that provide care and services for young children and their families.

Attendees are invited to:
- Participate in fun events at Let’s Play! including an obstacle course, giant block building, sensory walks, and dozens more
- Speak directly with representatives from Birth to 5 Community Coalition member organizations like local park districts, libraries, health and wellness experts, preschool and childcare options, behavior specialists, and organizations specifically for young parents
- Pick up giveaways and raffle prizes
- Obtain helpful literature from the Coalition members

Please SHARE with local families that might benefit!

post_text:
On Friday, 7th graders at Jay Stream Middle School participated in Career Day. After a keynote, they got to attend multiple sessions where they learned from professionals about what their jobs entail, what their interests were in school, and how they got where they are today.

Among the presenters were a mechanical engineer, physical therapist, insurance agent, agriculturist, veterinarian, nonprofit operations manager, probation officer, software engineer, professional musician, and medical device designer! It was a relevant educational opportunity for the students to think further about future career options as they consider their own personal paths.

post_text:
For the first time ever, CCSD93 is bringing together students with disabilities and students without to form a Unified Sports basketball team at each middle school that will eventually compete against other area schools!

The coed teams have begun weekly practices and are working towards a culminating tournament at Jay Stream on February 22 that will feature 11 middle schools, official referees and scorekeeping. The goal is for students to grow their basketball skills and abilities, camaraderie with one another, and leadership skills.

The basketball season is just the beginning, as CCSD93 hopes to expand offerings to additional sport seasons, with eyes on track, soccer, and more. Find out more!

post_text:
On Friday, Stratford Middle School 8th graders participated in College Day, which was an opportunity for them to learn about post-high school options of all kinds, not just traditional universities. After a keynote from Superintendent Hill, students had the opportunity to learn from representatives from University of Illinois at Chicago, IBEW electrician training, Lewis University, the Peace Corps, Northern Illinois University, JCM Institute healthcare training, Your House Academy real estate training, and the U.S. Army.

It was a terrific hands-on way for students to start to think about what their educational and professional path may look like.

This week, CCSD93's schools are celebrating Hour of Code, a worldwide movement for students to learn computer programming skills. Today at Western Trails, students collaborated to take on unique coding lessons, including:
- Learning sequencing & de-bugging by coming up with commands for their teacher to follow.
- Practicing code on the Mac.
- Following sequence commands with a DANCE OFF!

Find out more in this video!

post_text:
CCSD93's schools are collecting items for the Village of Carol Stream's Christmas Sharing Program. Heritage Lakes has an innovative take on its collection by encouraging themed donation days this week!

Monday - Red Day - Students and staff wore red and brought in ketchup, pasta, or sauce!

Tuesday - Just Out of Bed - Students wore pajamas and brought in pancake mix, syrup, or oatmeal!

Today - Sox for a Box - Students wore crazy socks and brought in boxes of cereal!

Thursday - Superheroes for Soup - Huskies are invited to dress like a Superhero and bring in boxed or canned soup!

Friday - Cap it Off with Caps - Huskies are invited to cap off the Food Drive today by wearing a hat and donating hygiene products!

Here's a look at their collections through just the first two days! For more on the program, visit https://www.carolstream.org/Home/Components/News/News/282/

post_text:
This morning, 7th graders at Stratford Middle School participated in Career Day. After a keynote, they got to attend four sessions where they learned from professionals about what their jobs entail, what their interests were in school, and how they got where they are today.

Among the presenters were an engineer, insurance agent, agriculturist, veterinarian, medical device designer, program manager, firefighter, police officer, software engineer, 9-1-1 dispatcher, and even a professional bagpiper! It was an eye-opening relevant educational opportunity for the students to think further about future career options.

post_text:
Today, members of the Carol Stream Police Department gave away uniquely designed and packaged "Shoes for SuperHeroes" for specially chosen superhero students at Elsie Johnson School! CCSD93 Resource Officer Castro spoke with students about how they're superheroes for making positive choices every day, and how they can rely on our community's police officers to help them continue to be superheroes.

We’ve shared a bit about this program before. As the Police Department continues to distribute the shoes at each CCSD93 elementary school, check out the reactions of these students to the unique packaging, which features a cannister complete with superhero sounds, the shoes, and a cape string bag!
